# CHASSIS Enforcement Rules — Cursor
# Auto-loaded by Cursor. These rules are NOT optional.
# They apply to every file touch in this project, no exceptions, no shortcuts.

## HARD STOP — BEFORE TOUCHING ANY FILE

Complete ALL of the following before writing a single line of code:

1. Read CHASSIS_ROADMAP.md in full.
2. Read .chassis/rules.md in full.
3. Read .chassis/blueprint.md — confirm your change fits the project scope.
4. Read the [SCOPE] tag at the top of every file you plan to touch.
5. Read every [WARN] tag in or near the code you plan to change.
6. Check CHASSIS_ROADMAP.md for [DEAD] entries related to what you're about to do.

If any step is skipped, stop and complete it first.

## HARD STOP — AFTER EVERY FILE CHANGE

After every single file touch — one line, one comment, anything:

1. Open CHASSIS_ROADMAP.md
2. Add an entry: file changed, what changed, why, any risk introduced
3. Update the *Last updated:* line with today's date

No exceptions. A typo fix gets logged. A comment reword gets logged.

## File Size Hard Stop

File reaches 200 lines → stop editing → split by responsibility → [SCOPE] on each new file → compile → log in roadmap.
[NEXT] is not a substitute for splitting. It is a violation.

## Required Annotations

- New file: [SCOPE] at line 1
- New function: comment above it
- Fragile code: [WARN] above it
- Incomplete work: [NEXT] tag
- Failed approach: [DEAD] with explanation
- Completed TODO: change to [DONE]
- Removed code: [DEAD] log

## Comment Syntax

TypeScript/JavaScript: // [TAG]
Python/Shell/YAML:     # [TAG]
HTML/XML:              <!-- [TAG] -->
CSS/SCSS:              /* [TAG] */

## Consequence of Non-Compliance

Skipping these rules corrupts the project history chain that every future AI and human depends on.
CHASSIS exists to prevent this. You are in a CHASSIS project. Follow the rules.

Rules also exist in: CLAUDE.md, .chassis/rules.md, .windsurf/rules.md
